Sales per department over time

The objective of this notebook is to identify patterns across departments, such as median sales, standard deviations, potential seasonality patterns and more.

Key findings:

  1. Foods seel the most volume and have the most number of unique items.
  2. Household items sell almost the same as hobbies, but have the double unique items as hobbies.
  3. There are significant differences in sales volume between hobbies 1 and hobbies 2 and between household 1 and household 2.
  4. foods 1 and household items have the potential of being seasonal items.

# Distribution of sales by month
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import kruskal

# category plots
def plot_categories_over_time():
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    for category in ["FOODS", "HOBBIES", "HOUSEHOLD"]:
        item_sales_focus = item_sales[item_sales['ctx_cat_id'] == category]
        sns.lineplot(
            data=item_sales_focus.groupby('ctx_date_month')['tgt_monthly_sales'].median().reset_index(),
            x='ctx_date_month', y='tgt_monthly_sales', marker='o', label=category)
    plt.title('Median Monthly Sales Per Category Over Time')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Median Sales')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(title='Category')
    plt.show()

def plot_number_unique_items_per_month_by_category():
    # Number of unique items per month for each category
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    for category in ["FOODS", "HOBBIES", "HOUSEHOLD"]:
        item_sales_focus = item_sales[item_sales['ctx_cat_id'] == category]
        unique_items_per_month = item_sales_focus.groupby(['ctx_date_month', "ctx_cat_id"])['ctx_item_id'].nunique().reset_index()
        sns.lineplot(
            data=unique_items_per_month,
            x='ctx_date_month', y='ctx_item_id', marker='o', label=category)
    plt.title('Number of Unique Items per Month by Category')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Unique Items')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(title='Category')
    plt.show()


# department plots
def plot_departments_over_time(dept_list):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    for dept in dept_list:
        item_sales_focus = item_sales[item_sales['ctx_dept_id'] == dept]
        sns.lineplot(
                data=item_sales_focus.groupby('ctx_date_month')['tgt_monthly_sales'].median().reset_index(),
                x='ctx_date_month', y='tgt_monthly_sales', marker='o', label=dept)
    plt.title('Median Monthly Sales Per Department Over Time')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Median Sales')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(title='Department')
    plt.show()

def plot_number_unique_items_per_month_by_department(dept_list):
    # Number of unique items per month for each department
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    for dept in dept_list:
        item_sales_focus = item_sales[item_sales['ctx_dept_id'] == dept]
        unique_items_per_month = item_sales_focus.groupby(['ctx_date_month', "ctx_dept_id"])['ctx_item_id'].nunique().reset_index()
        sns.lineplot(
            data=unique_items_per_month,
            x='ctx_date_month', y='ctx_item_id', marker='o', label=dept)
    plt.title('Number of Unique Items per Month by Deptarment')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Unique Items')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(title='Category')
    plt.show()

def plot_quantiles_over_time_for_specific_dept(dept):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    # filter by department
    item_sales_focus = item_sales[item_sales['ctx_dept_id'] == dept]
    # Plot each quantile: 
    sns.lineplot(data=item_sales_focus.groupby('ctx_date_month')[['tgt_monthly_sales']].quantile(.25).reset_index(),
        x='ctx_date_month', y='tgt_monthly_sales', marker='o', label=f"{dept}_q25")
    sns.lineplot(data=item_sales_focus.groupby('ctx_date_month')[['tgt_monthly_sales']].quantile(.5).reset_index(),
        x='ctx_date_month', y='tgt_monthly_sales', marker='o', label=f"{dept}_q50")
    sns.lineplot(data=item_sales_focus.groupby('ctx_date_month')[['tgt_monthly_sales']].quantile(.75).reset_index(),
        x='ctx_date_month', y='tgt_monthly_sales', marker='o', label=f"{dept}_q75")
    plt.title('Quantiles of Monthly Sales Per Department Over Time')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Sales')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(title='Department')
    plt.show()


def test_seasonality(dept_name):
    isoltated_dept = item_sales[item_sales["ctx_dept_id"]==dept_name]
    median_sales = isoltated_dept.groupby('ctx_date_month')['tgt_monthly_sales'].median().reset_index()

    median_sales["ctx_date_month"] = pd.to_datetime(median_sales["ctx_date_month"])
    median_sales['month'] = median_sales['ctx_date_month'].dt.month
    month_groups = [median_sales[median_sales['month']==m]['tgt_monthly_sales'] for m in range(1,13)]
    stat, p = kruskal(*month_groups)
    print(f'Kruskal-Wallis H-test statistic: {stat:.2f}, p-value: {p:.4f}')
    if p < 0.05:
        print('=> Significant evidence of seasonality (monthly effects)')
    else:
        print('=> No significant seasonality detected')
